                    </collation>
                    <condition key="deficient">Remains of two chant manuscrips, 
                      three quires of <ref target="#p1">Unit 1</ref> and one quire of <ref target="#p2">Unit 2</ref>, loosely 
                      held together.
                    The leaves <locus target="#1r #1v"/> are darkened, with the text partly abraided and unreadable.
                      The leaves of <ref target="#p2"/> are badly damaged by water in the lower half, 
                      the text having been made fully unreadable. The parchment of <ref target="#p1">Unit 1</ref> is stiff.
                    The leaf <locus target="#17"/> has a cut skilfully repaired.</condition>
                  </supportDesc>
                </objectDesc>  
                
                
                <bindingDesc>
                   <binding xml:id="binding">
                    <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="Other">The manuscript, composed of four quires originating from 
                      two different volumes, has no binding.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote xml:id="b2">Originally probably 4 sewing stations (see the centrefold between <locus target="#8"/> and <locus target="#9"/>; hardly possible to establish for <ref target="#p2">Unit 2</ref>). The quires are loosely held together 
                     by means of threads made of wrapped parchment strips and vegetal threads (both unlikely original).</decoNote>
                     <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Other">One hole is visible in the centrefold (between the leaves <locus target="#8"/> and <locus target="#9"/>), some 20 mm from the upper edge, possibly used for tacketing.</decoNote>
                  </binding>
                </bindingDesc>
              </physDesc>                                 
              <history>
                <summary><ref target="#p1">Unit 1</ref> and <ref target="#p2">Unit 2</ref> are remains of two different manuscripts 
                  of similar dimensions, containing texts of the same genre (chants).                   
                  <ref target="#p1">Unit 1</ref> might be dated to the period <date>second quarter to the late 14th century</date>.
                  <ref target="#p2">Unit 2</ref> appears to be somewhat older, <date>second half of the 13th to the early 14th century</date>.</summary>               
              </history>
              
              <additional>
                <adminInfo>
                  <recordHist>
                    <source>                      
                    </source>
                  </recordHist>
                </adminInfo>
                
              </additional>
              
              <msPart xml:id="p1">
                <msIdentifier/>
              
               <msContents>
                  <summary/>
                 
                 <msItem xml:id="p1_i1">
                      <locus from="1r" to="18v"/>
                   <title type="incomplete" cert="medium" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2361somade">Eight groups of chants (all in all 73), 
                     predominantly for fasting time; some are found in 
                     the contemporary printed Ṣoma dǝggʷā editions</title>
                      <textLang mainLang="gez"/> 
                   <incipit xml:lang="gez">
                   </incipit>
                   <note>No indications to chant types or melodic families; the rubricated numbers in the beginning of many chants 
                     appear to refer to hallelluiahs.  
                     One chant on <locus target="#16r"/> has an indication <foreign xml:lang="gez">በ<hi rend="rub">ዘጽባሕ፡</hi></foreign>.
                     Abbreviated refrains (one or rarely two letters) are used in many chants.</note>
                   
                    </msItem>
                 
               </msContents>
                
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="Codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>
                           <material key="parchment"/>
                        </support>
                        <extent>
                          <measure unit="leaf" quantity="18">18</measure>
                      <measure unit="quire" quantity="3">3</measure>
                        </extent>
                        <condition key="deficient"/>
                         </supportDesc>

                     <layoutDesc>                     
                           <layout columns="1" writtenLines="22">
                             <locus from="1r" to="18v"/>
                             <note>All data from <locus target="#7r"/>.</note>
                             <dimensions unit="mm" xml:id="textarea1">                              
                               <height>140</height>
                               <width>80</width>
                               </dimensions>
                             <dimensions type="margin" unit="mm" xml:id="margin">
                               <dim type="top">18</dim>
                               <dim type="bottom">24</dim>
                               <dim type="right">24</dim>
                             </dimensions>
                             <ab type="pricking">Primary pricks are partly visible.</ab>
                             <ab type="pricking">Text pricks are visible.</ab>
                             <ab type="ruling">Ruling is visible.</ab>   
                           <ab type="ruling" subtype="pattern">1A-1A/0-0/0-0/C</ab>
                             <ab type="ruling"> The upper line is written below the ruling.</ab>
                             <ab type="ruling"> The bottom line is written above the ruling.</ab>
                             <note>The horizontal ruled lines end at the text pricks, deep in the lateral margins 
                               (but at the vertical bounding ruled line after <locus target="#13"/>).</note>
                           </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                 
            <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                       <seg type="script"><date>14th-century</date> script.</seg> 
                       <date notBefore="1330" notAfter="1380"/>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                       <seg type="rubrication"/>
                       <desc>Regular, careful; by a good scribe. Ca. 13-14 character per written line. The word for God 
                         is written as one unit (<foreign xml:lang="gez">እግዚአብሔር፡</foreign>), in few cases as two units (<foreign xml:lang="gez">እግዚአ፡ ብሔር፡</foreign>), 
                         e.g., <locus target="#1r #5r #18r"/>.
                         Probably of somewhat later time as <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref>. <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref> is very similar or perhaps even identical
                         to the hand of <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BAVet25">Vatican City, Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana, Aeth. 25</ref>; similar to the hand of 
                         <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESdz001#p2"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: ESdz001#p2</span></ref> and comparable to the hand of <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/EStgm003#p1"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: EStgm003#p1</span></ref>. </desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                 <origin>
                   <origDate notBefore="1330" notAfter="1380" evidence="lettering">Second quarter to late 14th century</origDate>.
                 </origin>
               </history>
              </msPart>
              
              <msPart xml:id="p2">
                <msIdentifier/>
                
                <msContents>
                  <summary/>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="p2_i1">
                    <locus from="19r" to="22v"/>
                    <title type="incomplete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3178Deggwa">Three groups of chants (at least 33) dedicated apparently to the Holy Cross; possibly of mazmur-type. Some of the chants 
                      are found in the contemporary printed Dǝggʷā editions</title>
                    <textLang mainLang="gez"/> 
                    <incipit xml:lang="gez"><hi rend="rubric">ዘሂ፡ በካልእ፡ ዜማ፡ </hi> እግዚኦ፡ <sic resp="DN">አለ፡ ኬድካ፡</sic> አምነ፡ ብከ፡
                      ይድኅኑ፡ ወ<add place="above">እ</add>ለ፡ ኪያከ፡ አ<gap reason="lost" unit="chars" quantity="2"/><supplied reason="lost" resp="DN">በ</supplied>ስመ፡ 
                      ዚአከ፡ ዐቢይ፡ ኀይለ፡ ይገብሩ፡                    
                      
                    </incipit>
                    <note>The exact number of chants is difficult to establish because of the poor condition of the fragment. 
                      A rubricated indication to the melody is at the beginning of each group; the term <foreign xml:lang="gez"><hi rend="rubric">ህላዌ፡ መስቀል፡</hi></foreign>
                      is used on <locus target="#21v"/> (on this, cp. <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/KR6I2QMX"><seg type="thesis"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Karlsson2022DiachDeggwa"/><title level="m">The Diachronic Development of the &lt;hi rend="italics"&gt;Dǝggʷā&lt;/hi&gt;: A Study in Texts and Manuscripts of Selected Ethiopic Antiphon Collections</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Jonas</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Karlsson</t:surname></author><pubPlace>Hamburg</pubPlace><date>2022</date><note type="thesisType">PhD Dissertation</note><citedRange unit="page">94, esp. footnote 23</citedRange></bibl>).</note>
                  </msItem>   
                </msContents>
                                
                <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="Codex">
                    <supportDesc>
                      <support>
                        <material key="parchment"/>
                      </support>
                      <extent>
                        <measure unit="leaf" quantity="4">4</measure>
                        <locus from="19" to="22"/>
                        <measure unit="quire" quantity="1">1</measure>
                      </extent>
                      <condition key="deficient"/>
                    </supportDesc>
                    
                    <layoutDesc>                    
                      <layout columns="1" writtenLines="28" cert="low">
                        <locus from="19r" to="22v"/>
                        <note>The number of written lines is taken from <locus target="#20v"/>. The number of written lines 
                         can be retrieved very approximately since the the lower part of the leaf is destroyed.</note>
                        <note>The dimensions taken from <locus target="#19r"/>, very approximately 
                          since the text on the lower part of the leaf is destroyed.</note>
                        <dimensions unit="mm" xml:id="textarea2">                          
                          <height>137</height>
                          <width>103</width>
                        </dimensions>
                        <ab type="pricking">Primary pricks are not visible.</ab>
                        <ab type="pricking">Text pricks are not visible.</ab>
                        <ab type="ruling">Ruling is partly visible.</ab>   
                        <ab type="ruling" subtype="pattern">1A-1A/0-0/0-0/C</ab>
                        <ab type="ruling"> The upper line is written below the ruling.</ab>
                        <note>The vertical bounding ruled lines and the text pricks are 
                          not visible due to the poor condition of the leaves.</note> 
                      </layout>
                    </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  
                  <handDesc>
                    <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">
                      <seg type="script">Second half of the 13th-/<date>early 14th-century</date> script.</seg> 
                        <date notBefore="1250" notAfter="1399"/>
                        <seg type="ink">Black (bleak), red.</seg>
                      <seg type="rubrication">Executed possibly by a different hand.</seg>
                      <desc>Regular, careful; by a good scribe. Small script, the line accomodates ca. 24-25 characters. 
                        The vowel marker of <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስ</foreign> is composed of a short line directed to the left, 
                        set up upon a vertical line but also the standard medieval shape is used. <ref target="#h2">Hand 2</ref>
                      is probably older that <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref>. Vocalization is not always that of standard Gǝʿǝz, in some (not many) words it is "odd".
                        The Gǝʿǝz word for God is not used in the readable text of the fragment.</desc>                     
                    </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                </physDesc>
                  
                <history>
                  <origin>
                    <origDate notBefore="1250" notAfter="1330" evidence="lettering">Second half of the 13th-/early 14th-century</origDate>.
                  </origin>
                </history>
              </msPart>
            </msDesc>

